 [[Lev Psakhis]] +4, -0, =2 in [[Murcia]], Spain.\n*A 'Chess Summit', held in [[Reykjav\u00edk]], comprises four teams of ten players. The USSR wins (31\u00bd/60) ahead of England (31/60), USA (30/60) and a combined 'Nordic countries' team (27\u00bd/60). England records its first ever match victory over the Soviet team with a 6-4 result.\n*Beliavsky, [[Leonid Yudasin]], [[Evgeny Bareev]] and [[Alexey Vyzmanavin]] tie for first place in the penultimate [[USSR Chess Championship]], held in Leningrad (soon to be renamed [[Saint Petersburg]]). Beliavsky is awarded the title on tie-break.\n*[[Lev Alburt]] wins the [[US Chess Championship]] in [[Jacksonville]]. [[Elena Donaldson]] takes the Women's Championship, held in [[Spartanburg]], South Carolina.\n*[[James Plaskett]] is the winner of the [[British Chess Championship]], held at [[Eastbourne]]. [[Susan Arkell]] is the Women's Champion.\n*[[Igor Glek]] wins the World Open in [[Philadelphia]].\n*Khalifman wins the New York Open and [[Bent Larsen]] takes the ([[Watson, Farley & Williams]]) New York International with 6\u00bd/9, ahead of [[Vasilios Kotronias]] (6/9).\n*The US Masters in [[Chicago]] is won by [[Tony Miles]].\n*Karpov wins a game against [[Deep Thought (chess computer)|Deep Thought]] at [[Harvard]]. The program, created by scientists at [[Carnegie-Mellon University]], is remotely attached to an [[IBM]] Mainframe, enabling it to examine 750,000 positions per second.\n*Seirawan defeats Timman 4-2 in the annual KRO Exhibition Match, held in [[Hilversum]]. This is one in a novel series of matches in which Timman is pitted against his contemporary grandmaster rivals.\n*The [[World Youth Chess Championship]] for older children is held in [[Singapore]]. [[Sergei Tiviakov]] wins the Boys Under-18, while [[Konstantin Sakaev]] takes the Boys Under-16 trophy. [[Tea Lanchava]] of Georgia wins in the Girls Under-16 category.\n* The [[World Youth Chess Championship|World Youth Chess Festival for Peace]] caters for the younger children at [[Fond du Lac, Wisconsin|Fond du Lac]], Wisconsin. Although there are categories for girls, Hungarian child prodigy [[Judit Polg\u00e1r]] enters and wins the Boys Under-14 section. This repeats her (Under-12) achievement at [[Timi\u015foara]] in 1988. [[Boris Avrukh]] of the Soviet Union wins the Boys Under-12 category.\n*England and the USSR tie for first place in the [[World Chess Solving Championship]].\n*[[FIDE]] declares that smoking is prohibited at all of its events.\n*''[[Shakhmatny Bulletin]]'' ceases publication.\n*''[[Variant Chess]]'' begins publication.\n\n==Births==\n\n*[[Magnus Carlsen]], Norwegian player, world top five Grandmaster while still a junior - November 30\n*[[Sergey Karjakin]], Ukrainian player, youngest Grandmaster ever and a World Youth Champion - January 12\n*[[Ian Nepomniachtchi]], Russian Grandmaster, World Youth Champion at U-14 - July 14\n*[[Maxime Vachier-Lagrave]], French Grandmaster and national champion - October 21\n*[[Dmitry Andreikin]], Russian Grandmaster and former World Junior Champion - February 5\n*[[Yuriy Kuzubov]], Ukrainian Grandmaster, one of the world's youngest to gain the title - January 26\n*[[Anna Muzychuk]], IM from Ukraine then Slovenia, World Youth Champion for Girls U-16 - February 28\n*[[Nguyen Ngoc Truong Son]], Vietnamese player, World Youth Champion at U-10 - February 23\n*[[David Howell (chess player)|David Howell]], England's youngest ever Grandmaster - November 14\n*[[Puchen Wang]], New Zealand International Master - January 20\n*[[Anya Corke]], Hong Kong WGM, winner of three (Open section) British Junior titles - September 12\n\n==Deaths==\n\n*[[Alexander Konstantinopolsky]], Ukrainian honorary Grandmaster, Correspondence player and trainer - September 21\n*[[Eero B\u00f6\u00f6k]], Finnish player, honorary Grandmaster and six-time national champion - January 7\n*[[Guillermo Garcia Gonzales]], Cuban Grandmaster, three-time national champion - October 26\n*[[Ernest Klein (chess player)|Ernest Klein]], former British champion and author - ?\n*[[Emil Josef Diemer]] - German player and openings theorist - October 10\n*[[Geza Fuster]], Hungarian-Canadian International Master - ?\n*[[Ernest Pogosyants]], Ukrainian chess problemist and endgame study specialist - August 16\n*[[Baldur Honlinger]], prominent Austrian player of the 1920s-1950s - March 12\n*[[Heinrich Reinhardt]], German-Austrian player - June 14\n\n==References==\n\n*{{cite book | author=Burgess, Graham | title=Chess Highlights of  the 20th Century | publisher=Gambit Publications | year=1999 | isbn=1-901983-21-8}}\n*[http://www.geocities.com/SiliconValley/Lab/7378/history.txt Chess History & Chronology - Bill Wall] ([https://www.webcitation.org/query?id=1256043111937372 Archived] 2009-10-20)\n*[http://www.olimpbase.org Olimpbase - Olympiads and other Team event information]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091126000035/http://chess.eusa.ed.ac.uk/Chess/Trivia/AlltimeList.html FIDE rating list data 1970-97]\n*[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0CE7DF173BF937A25753C1A966958260 NY Times (Robert Byrne) account of New York International]\n*[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0CE4D91038F932A2575AC0A966958260 NY Times (Robert Byrne) account of Biel Tournament]\n\n{{chess}}\n\n[[Category:1990 in chess| ]]\n[[Category:20th century in chess]]\n[[Category:Chess by year]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "Timi\u0219oara(viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1990_in_chess"}
{"title_page": "Diadocidiidae", "text_new": "{{short description|Family of flies}}\n{{Taxobox\n| name = Diadocidiidae\n| image = \n| fossil_range = [[Cretaceous]]<ref>Blagoderov, V. & Grimaldi, D.A. Fossil Sciaroidea (Diptera) in Cretaceous Ambers, Exclusive of Cecidomyiidae, Sciaridae, and Keroplatidae. [[American Museum Novitates]] 3433 (2004)</ref> - recent\n| regnum = [[Animal]]ia\n| phylum = [[Arthropod]]a\n| classis = [[Insect]]a\n| ordo = [[Fly|Diptera]]\n| subordo = [[Nematocera]]\n| infraordo = [[Bibionomorpha]]\n| superfamilia = [[Sciaroidea]]\n| familia = '''Diadocidiidae'''\n| familia_authority = [[Johannes Winnertz|Winnertz]], 1863\n| diversity_link = list of mycetophilid/keroplatid genera\n| diversity = 23 species\n| subdivision_ranks = Genera\n| subdivision = *''[[Diadocidia]]''\n*\u2020''[[Docidiadia]]''\n}}\nThe '''Diadocidiidae''' are a [[Family (biology)|family]] of [[fly|flies]] (Diptera).\nTwo genera with over 20 species are described.<ref>Jaschhof, M., Jaschhof,C. On the genus Diadocidia (Diptera, Sciaroidea, Diadocidiidae) in Costa Rica. [[Zootaxa]] 1586: 33\u201338 (2007)</ref><ref>Jaschhof, M., Jaschhof,C. On the genus Diadocidia (Diptera, Sciaroidea, Diadocidiidae) in Australia. [[Zootaxa]] 1655: 63\u201368 (2007)</ref> Diadocidiidae are found worldwide, except in [[Africa]] and [[Antarctica]]. They are usually considered close to the [[Keroplatidae]], [[Bolitophilidae]], and [[Ditomyiidae]],<ref>Hippa, H. & Vilkamaa, P. 2005. Phylogeny of the Sciaroidea (Diptera): the implication of additional taxa and character data. [[Zootaxa]] 1132, 63-68 (2006)</ref> and used to be included in the [[Mycetophilidae]]. They are [[woodland]] flies. The larvae spin silken tubes under bark or in dead logs.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*La\u0161tovka P. & Matile L. 1972 R\u00e9vision des Diadocidia Holarctiques [Dipt. Mycetophilidae].'' [[Annales de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Entomologique de France]]'' (N. S.) 8: 205-223.\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikispecies| Diadocidiidae}}\n*[http://www.eol.org/pages/469 EOL]\n*[http://www.diptera.info/photogallery.php?album_id=119 Diptera.info] Image\n\n{{Diptera}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2213523}}\n\n[[Category:Nematocera families]]\n[[Category:Sciaroidea]]\n[[Category:Diadocidiidae| ]]\n{{Sciaroidea-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Family of flies}}\n{{Taxobox\n| name = Diadocidiidae\n| image = \n| fossil_range = [[Cretaceous]]<ref>Blagoderov, V. & Grimaldi, D.A. Fossil Sciaroidea (Diptera) in Cretaceous Ambers, Exclusive of Cecidomyiidae, Sciaridae, and Keroplatidae. [[American Museum Novitates]] 3433 (2004)</ref> - recent\n| regnum = [[Animal]]ia\n| phylum = [[Arthropod]]a\n| classis = [[Insect]]a\n| ordo = [[Fly|Diptera]]\n| subordo = [[Nematocera]]\n| infraordo = [[Bibionomorpha]]\n| superfamilia = [[Sciaroidea]]\n| familia = '''Diadocidiidae'''\n| familia_authority = [[Johannes Winnertz|Winnertz]], 1863\n| diversity_link = list of mycetophilid/keroplatid genera\n| diversity = 23 species\n| subdivision_ranks = Genera\n| subdivision = *''[[Diadocidia]]''\n*''[[Palaeodocidia]]''\n*\u2020''[[Docidiadia]]''\n}}\nThe '''Diadocidiidae''' are a [[Family (biology)|family]] of [[fly|flies]] (Diptera).\nTwo genera with over 20 species are described.<ref>Jaschhof, M., Jaschhof,C. On the genus Diadocidia (Diptera, Sciaroidea, Diadocidiidae) in Costa Rica. [[Zootaxa]] 1586: 33\u201338 (2007)</ref><ref>Jaschhof, M., Jaschhof,C. On the genus Diadocidia (Diptera, Sciaroidea, Diadocidiidae) in Australia. [[Zootaxa]] 1655: 63\u201368 (2007)</ref> Diadocidiidae are found worldwide, except in [[Africa]] and [[Antarctica]]. They are usually considered close to the [[Keroplatidae]], [[Bolitophilidae]], and [[Ditomyiidae]],<ref>Hippa, H. & Vilkamaa, P. 2005. Phylogeny of the Sciaroidea (Diptera): the implication of additional taxa and character data. [[Zootaxa]] 1132, 63-68 (2006)</ref> and used to be included in the [[Mycetophilidae]]. They are [[woodland]] flies. The larvae spin silken tubes under bark or in dead logs.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*La\u0161tovka P. & Matile L. 1972 R\u00e9vision des Diadocidia Holarctiques [Dipt. Mycetophilidae].'' [[Annales de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Entomologique de France]]'' (N. S.) 8: 205-223.\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikispecies| Diadocidiidae}}\n*[http://www.eol.org/pages/469 EOL]\n*[http://www.diptera.info/photogallery.php?album_id=119 Diptera.info] Image\n\n{{Diptera}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2213523}}\n\n[[Category:Nematocera families]]\n[[Category:Sciaroidea]]\n[[Category:Diadocidiidae| ]]\n{{Sciaroidea-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Dyanega", "label": "safe", "comment": "rv invalid genus", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diadocidiidae"}
{"title_page": "Haribo", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{refimprove|date=July 2010}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Haribo\n| logo             = HARIBO Logo.svg\n| logo_size        = 220px\n| image            = 2013-09-02 Haribo-Zentrale, Hans-Riegel-Stra\u00dfe 1, Bonn-Kessenich IMG 0929.jpg\n| image_caption    = Former Haribo headquarters in [[Bonn]]-[[Kessenich (Bonn)|Kessenich]]\n| type             = [[Kommanditgesellschaft|GmbH & Co. KG]]\n| founder          = [[Hans Riegel Sr.]]\n| key_people       = \n| industry         = [[Confectionery]]\n| products         = Gummy bears, gummy candy\n| revenue          = [[Euro|\u20ac]] 1.7\u20132.0 billion\n| num_employees    = ~7,000 (2018)\n| homepage         = {{URL|http://www.haribo.com}}\n| foundation       = {{Start date and age|1920|12|12}}\n| location_city    = [[Grafschaft, Rhineland]]\n| location_country = Germany\n}}\n'''Haribo''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|h|\u00e6r|\u1d7b|b|o\u028a}} {{respell|HARR|i-boh}}) is a German [[confectionery]] company founded by [[Hans Riegel Sr.]] in 1920. It began in [[Kessenich (Bonn)|Kessenich]], [[Bonn]], [[North Rhine-Westphalia]]; the name is an [[acronym]] formed from '''Ha'''ns '''Ri'''egel, '''Bo'''nn. The company created the first [[Gummy candy|gummy candy]] in 1922 in the form of little [[Gummy bear|gummy bears]] called ''Gummib\u00e4rchen''. The current headquarters is in [[Grafschaft, Rhineland|Grafschaft]], [[Rhineland-Palatinate]], Germany.\n\nThe [[Museum|Landesmuseum]] [[Koblenz]] created a travelling exhibition about the history of Haribo in 2006.\n\n==History==\n\n\nHaribo has expanded its operations, taking over many local confectionery manufacturers in countries all over the world. It began international expansion in the 1960s and entered American markets in the 1980s. It currently operates 16 factories which produce over 100 million gummy bears per day.<ref name=guardian>{{cite news|last1=Oltermann|first1=Philip|title=Haribo: the confessions of a confectionery addict|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/shortcuts/2013/oct/16/haribo-confectionery-founder-hans-riegel-died-90|accessdate=30 July 2015|work=The Guardian|date=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nHaribo was accused of using [[Forced labour in Germany during World War II|Jewish forced labor]] in its factories during [[World War II]], but denies this.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Charles P. |last=Wallace |title=The Final Reckoning |url=http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2050858,00.html |journal=[[Time (magazine)|Time Europe]] |location=Berlin |volume=156 |issue=5 |date=31 July 2000 |accessdate=12 November 2008}}</ref> In 2014, Haribo's ''Skipper Mix'' was pulled in some markets because some of the candy pieces were shaped like caricatures of Asian, African, and Native American masks that some consumers considered to be racist.<ref>{{cite news|last=Licata|first=Elizabeth|title=Haribo Pulls Skipper Mix After Racism Accusations|url=http://www.thedailymeal.com/Haribo-Pulls-Skipper-Mix-Racism-Accusations/11814|accessdate=25 January 2015|newspaper=The Daily Meal|date=18 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==UK presence==<!--{{Pontefract}} links here-->\n[[File:German sweets and liquorice confectionery.jpg|thumb|A colourful mix of confectionery: Haribo Colour-Rado]]\n[[File:Haribo Sweets Factory - Sessions House Yard - geograph.org.uk - 576986.jpg|thumb|left|Haribo factory in [[Pontefract]].]]\nHaribo's key brands in the UK are Starmix, Tangfastics, Supermix, and Maoam, with Maoam being its own line of chewy sweets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maoam.com/lang/enGB/index.html|title=MAOAM|work=maoam.com|accessdate=27 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150719065925/http://www.maoam.com/lang/enGB/index.html|archivedate=19 July 2015}}</ref> They were once the distributor of [[Pez]] products in the United Kingdom, but this is no longer the case. Haribo makes [[Pontefract Cakes]] at their factory in [[Pontefract]], [[West Yorkshire]], and other locations.\n\n==US presence==\n\n{{Unreferenced section|date=December 2019}}\n\nHaribo had been imported into the [[United States]] for many years{{When|date=May 2017}} by German food importers and sold at German and other gourmet stores at \"gourmet prices\", mostly in bulk. In Germany, Haribo was not an exclusive gourmet product, but a mass market candy. When Haribo of America was incorporated in the 1980s in [[Baltimore, Maryland]], Haribo's gummi candies were introduced to the US mass market through areas such as drugstores, grocery stores, and discount stores. The packaging was translated into English, and package weights were adjusted to match U.S. candy price points and package sizes. A laydown bag was developed for the US supermarket trade, instead of the hanging bag commonly found in German supermarkets, and a boxed product was developed for theaters. \n\nOnce this was done and Haribo products in US-style packaging were introduced at confectionery and fancy food shows, Haribo became a popular item. Sales soared the first year, and gummy bears became so popular in the US, Haribo in Germany could not supply enough products, so the US market was soon flooded with competitors such as German [[Trolli]] and American [[Black Forest Gummy Bears|Black Forest]].\n\nOn 23 March 2017, Haribo announced they will be opening their first United States factory, a 500,000 sq ft (46,500 m\u00b2), 400 employee manufacturing plant in Kenosha County, Wisconsin, scheduled to open in 2020.\nHaribo products made in the US regularly have [[corn syrup]] and artificial flavors and colors. Production with artificial ingredients is cheaper, however, and the U.S. operation is poised to profit from this lower cost.\n\n==International distribution==\n\n==Slogans==\nHaribo's [[German language|German]] catch phrase is ''\"Haribo macht Kinder froh \u2013 und Erwachsene ebenso\"'' (\"Haribo makes children happy \u2013 and adults as well\"). The German advertisements were voiced by [[Thomas Gottschalk]] from 1991 until 2015. In English-speaking countries, it uses the slogan \"Kids and grown-ups love it so \u2013 the happy world of Haribo\". In [[Hungary]], it uses the slogan \"''Gyermek, feln\u0151tt kedve j\u00f3 \u2013 \u00e9des \u00e9let, Haribo''\" (\"Child and adult is happy \u2013 sweet life, Haribo\"). \"''Haribo c'est beau la vie, pour les grands et les petits''\" (\"Haribo life is beautiful, for big ones and little ones\") is used in [[France]], while in [[Italy]] the song used during commercials is: \"''Haribo \u00e8 la bont\u00e0, che si gusta ad ogni et\u00e0''\" (\"Haribo is the delicacy that one can taste at any age\"). Similar slogans are used in other languages. The famed Haribo jingle music was created by UK composer Stephen Lee Vickers.\n\n==In popular culture==\nhey sup\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Haribo}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.haribo.com}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Food and drink companies established in 1920]]\n[[Category:Candy]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies of Germany]]\n[[Category:Brand name confectionery]]\n[[Category:German brands]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Bonn]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Rhineland-Palatinate]]\n[[Category:Ahrweiler (district)]]\n[[Category:German confectionery]]\n[[Category:Gummi candies]]\n[[Category:1920 establishments in Germany]]\n[[category:German snack foods]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{refimprove|date=July 2010}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Haribo\n| logo             = HARIBO Logo.svg\n| logo_size        = 220px\n| image            = 2013-09-02 Haribo-Zentrale, Hans-Riegel-Stra\u00dfe 1, Bonn-Kessenich IMG 0929.jpg\n| image_caption    = Former Haribo headquarters in [[Bonn]]-[[Kessenich (Bonn)|Kessenich]]\n| type             = [[Kommanditgesellschaft|GmbH & Co. KG]]\n| founder          = [[Hans Riegel Sr.]]\n| key_people       = \n| industry         = [[Confectionery]]\n| products         = Gummy bears, gummy candy\n| revenue          = [[Euro|\u20ac]] 1.7\u20132.0 billion\n| num_employees    = ~7,000 (2018)\n| homepage         = {{URL|http://www.haribo.com}}\n| foundation       = {{Start date and age|1920|12|12}}\n| location_city    = [[Grafschaft, Rhineland]]\n| location_country = Germany\n}}\n'''Haribo''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|h|\u00e6r|\u1d7b|b|o\u028a}} {{respell|HARR|i-boh}}) is a German [[confectionery]] company founded by [[Hans Riegel Sr.]] in 1920. It began in [[Kessenich (Bonn)|Kessenich]], [[Bonn]], [[North Rhine-Westphalia]]; the name is an [[acronym]] formed from '''Ha'''ns '''Ri'''egel, '''Bo'''nn. The company created the first [[Gummy candy|gummy candy]] in 1922 in the form of little [[Gummy bear|gummy bears]] called ''Gummib\u00e4rchen''. The current headquarters is in [[Grafschaft, Rhineland|Grafschaft]], [[Rhineland-Palatinate]], Germany.\n\nThe [[Museum|Landesmuseum]] [[Koblenz]] created a travelling exhibition about the history of Haribo in 2006.\n\n==History==\n\n\nHaribo has expanded its operations, taking over many local confectionery manufacturers in countries all over the world. It began international expansion in the 1960s and entered American markets in the 1980s. It currently operates 16 factories which produce over 100 million gummy bears per day.<ref name=guardian>{{cite news|last1=Oltermann|first1=Philip|title=Haribo: the confessions of a confectionery addict|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/shortcuts/2013/oct/16/haribo-confectionery-founder-hans-riegel-died-90|accessdate=30 July 2015|work=The Guardian|date=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nHaribo was accused of using [[Forced labour in Germany during World War II|Jewish forced labor]] in its factories during [[World War II]], but denies this.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Charles P. |last=Wallace |title=The Final Reckoning |url=http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2050858,00.html |journal=[[Time (magazine)|Time Europe]] |location=Berlin |volume=156 |issue=5 |date=31 July 2000 |accessdate=12 November 2008}}</ref> In 2014, Haribo's ''Skipper Mix'' was pulled in some markets because some of the candy pieces were shaped like caricatures of Asian, African, and Native American masks that some consumers considered to be racist.<ref>{{cite news|last=Licata|first=Elizabeth|title=Haribo Pulls Skipper Mix After Racism Accusations|url=http://www.thedailymeal.com/Haribo-Pulls-Skipper-Mix-Racism-Accusations/11814|accessdate=25 January 2015|newspaper=The Daily Meal|date=18 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==UK presence==<!--{{Pontefract}} links here-->\n[[File:German sweets and liquorice confectionery.jpg|thumb|A colourful mix of confectionery: Haribo Colour-Rado]]\n[[File:Haribo Sweets Factory - Sessions House Yard - geograph.org.uk - 576986.jpg|thumb|left|Haribo factory in [[Pontefract]].]]\nHaribo's key brands in the UK are Starmix, Tangfastics, Supermix, and Maoam, with Maoam being its own line of chewy sweets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maoam.com/lang/enGB/index.html|title=MAOAM|work=maoam.com|accessdate=27 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150719065925/http://www.maoam.com/lang/enGB/index.html|archivedate=19 July 2015}}</ref> They were once the distributor of [[Pez]] products in the United Kingdom, but this is no longer the case. Haribo makes [[Pontefract Cakes]] at their factory in [[Pontefract]], [[West Yorkshire]], and other locations.\n\n==US presence==\n\n{{Unreferenced section|date=December 2019}}\n\nHaribo had been imported into the [[United States]] for many years{{When|date=May 2017}} by German food importers and sold at German and other gourmet stores at \"gourmet prices\", mostly in bulk. In Germany, Haribo was not an exclusive gourmet product, but a mass market candy. When Haribo of America was incorporated in the 1980s in [[Baltimore, Maryland]], Haribo's gummi candies were introduced to the US mass market through areas such as drugstores, grocery stores, and discount stores. The packaging was translated into English, and package weights were adjusted to match U.S. candy price points and package sizes. A laydown bag was developed for the US supermarket trade, instead of the hanging bag commonly found in German supermarkets, and a boxed product was developed for theaters. \n\nOnce this was done and Haribo products in US-style packaging were introduced at confectionery and fancy food shows, Haribo became a popular item. Sales soared the first year, and gummy bears became so popular in the US, Haribo in Germany could not supply enough products, so the US market was soon flooded with competitors such as German [[Trolli]] and American [[Black Forest Gummy Bears|Black Forest]].\n\nOn 23 March 2017, Haribo announced they will be opening their first United States factory, a 500,000 sq ft (46,500 m\u00b2), 400 employee manufacturing plant in Kenosha County, Wisconsin, scheduled to open in 2020.\nHaribo products made in the US regularly have [[corn syrup]] and artificial flavors and colors. Production with artificial ingredients is cheaper, however, and the U.S. operation is poised to profit from this lower cost.\n\n==International distribution==\n[[File:Haribo Normanton Distribution.jpg|New Haribo factory and distribution centre located in Castleford, West Yorkshire, UK.|thumb]]\nHaribo plans to expand to China and Brazil. In China it has launched test stores in Shanghai and Guangdong. The US headquarters is located in [[Rosemont, IL]]. New production facilities opened in [[Castleford]], West Yorkshire,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leeds-24471417|title=Castleford Haribo plant to create 286 jobs|date=10 October 2013|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> (directly opposite the Normanton M62 Junction (J31)) in 2016 and plans to open in S\u00e3o Paulo, Brazil.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Best|first1=Dean|title=Haribo to expand in China, US, UK and Brazil|url=http://www.just-food.com/news/haribo-to-expand-in-china-us-uk-and-brazil_id130630.aspx|website=just-food.com|publisher=just-food.com|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref>[[File:Haribo factories in Europe.png|thumb|Countries with Haribo factories in Europe]]\n\n==Slogans==\nHaribo's [[German language|German]] catch phrase is ''\"Haribo macht Kinder froh \u2013 und Erwachsene ebenso\"'' (\"Haribo makes children happy \u2013 and adults as well\"). The German advertisements were voiced by [[Thomas Gottschalk]] from 1991 until 2015. In English-speaking countries, it uses the slogan \"Kids and grown-ups love it so \u2013 the happy world of Haribo\". In [[Hungary]], it uses the slogan \"''Gyermek, feln\u0151tt kedve j\u00f3 \u2013 \u00e9des \u00e9let, Haribo''\" (\"Child and adult is happy \u2013 sweet life, Haribo\"). \"''Haribo c'est beau la vie, pour les grands et les petits''\" (\"Haribo life is beautiful, for big ones and little ones\") is used in [[France]], while in [[Italy]] the song used during commercials is: \"''Haribo \u00e8 la bont\u00e0, che si gusta ad ogni et\u00e0''\" (\"Haribo is the delicacy that one can taste at any age\"). Similar slogans are used in other languages. The famed Haribo jingle music was created by UK composer Stephen Lee Vickers.\n\n==In popular culture==\n*Haribo is referred to by name in [[Watsky]]'s 2012 song \"Gummy Bear Hundrednaire\" off his [[mix-tape]] ''Nothing Like the First Time''.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bft9zX5VSWw</ref><ref>https://gwatsky.bandcamp.com/album/nothing-like-the-first-time</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Haribo}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.haribo.com}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Food and drink companies established in 1920]]\n[[Category:Candy]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies of Germany]]\n[[Category:Brand name confectionery]]\n[[Category:German brands]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Bonn]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Rhineland-Palatinate]]\n[[Category:Ahrweiler (district)]]\n[[Category:German confectionery]]\n[[Category:Gummi candies]]\n[[Category:1920 establishments in Germany]]\n[[category:German snack foods]]\n", "name_user": "72.213.157.141", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eIn popular culture:I am among)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haribo"}
{"title_page": "Park National Bank (Ohio)", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{Refimprove|date=February 2013}}\n{{Notability|Companies|date=February 2013}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Park National Bank\n| logo             = [[File:Park National Bank logo 2013.png|250px|Park National Bank logo]]\n| former type      = \n| type             = [[Subsidiary]]\n| traded_as        = \n| industry         = Banking\n| fate             = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| foundation       = <!-- City, Country ({{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}}) -->\n| founder          = \n| defunct          = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| location_city    = \n| location_country = \n| locations        = <!-- Number of locations, stores, offices &c. -->\n| area_served      = {{ubl|[[Ohio]]|[[Kentucky]]|[[North Carolina]]}}\n| key_people       =  \n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = $84.2 million (2017)<ref name=\"ND Acq\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/columbus/news/2018/01/23/park-national-bank-to-buy-charlotte-based-bank-for.html |title=Park National Bank to buy Charlotte-based bank for $76M |last=Navera |first=Tristan |website=[[Columbus Business First]] |date=2018-01-23 |accessdate=2018-01-24}}</ref>\n| aum              = $7.5 billion (2017)<ref name=\"ND Acq\"/>\n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| owner            = \n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = Park National Corporation\n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = {{url|www.parknationalbank.com}}\n| footnotes        = \n}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Park National Corporation\n| traded_as = {{AMEX|PRK}}<br>[[Russell 2000 Index|Russell 2000 Component]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Park National Bank''' is the lead bank in the $7.5 billion Park National Corporation ({{AMEX|PRK}}) serving [[Ohio]] and Northern [[Kentucky]]. The bank has 10 affiliate banks, including: Fairfield National Bank; Park National Bank, Park National Bank: Southwest Ohio & Northern Kentucky; United Bank; First-Knox National Bank; Richland Bank; Second National Bank; Security National Bank; Unity National Bank; NewDominion Bank; Carolina Alliance Bank; Guardian Finance Company; Southeast Property Holdings; and Scope Leasing. Park National Bank is headquartered in [[Newark, Ohio]].\n\n== History ==\nPark National Bank was founded in July 1908 under the name The Park National Bank of Newark.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parknationalbank.com/|title=Home - Park National|website=Park National|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref> The organization changed its name to Park National Bank in 1971 shortly after acquiring The People's State Bank. The company then acquired The Utica Savings Bank Company in 1973, followed by The Fairfield National Bank of Lancaster.\n\nDuring the housing crisis of the early 2000s, Park National acquired nine other banks in a three year period.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bankbranchlocator.com/park-national-bank-history.html|title=Park National Bank History|website=www.bankbranchlocator.com|language=en|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref> Most of these acquisitions happened within the 2008 fiscal year, which was the peak of the crisis.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thebalance.com/mortgage-crisis-overview-315684|title=What (or Who) Caused the Mortgage Crisis?|work=The Balance|access-date=2018-11-02|language=en}}</ref> The company managed to acquire seven different banks in 2008. The next acquisition for the corporation was NewDominion Bank, which brought Park National into the North Carolina area. One of their affiliates has also recently announced plans to build a location in Kentucky.\n\nThe Carolina Alliance Bank is the latest bank to join the organization expanding the region into South Carolina.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newarkadvocate.com/story/news/2018/09/14/park-national-announces-plan-acquire-south-carolina-bank/1291606002/|title=Park National announces plan to acquire South Carolina bank|work=The Newark Advocate|access-date=2018-11-02|language=en}}</ref> The Park National Family of Banks is now operating in 28 counties in Ohio, one in Kentucky, one in North Carolina, and two in South Carolina. There are 110 branches located in Ohio.\n\n== Affiliates ==\n\n=== Fairfield National Bank ===\nThis affiliate started with the acquisition of The Fairfield National Bank of Lancaster in 1985. Fairfield National has nine branches, the main branch is in downtown Lancaster. They have locations in Lancaster, Baltimore, Pickerington, and Canal Winchester. The president of this division is Laura Tussing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fairfieldnationalbank.com/|title=Home - Fairfield National Bank|website=Fairfield National Bank|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Park National Bank: Southwest Ohio and Northern Kentucky ===\nThis affiliate started with the acquisition of First Clermont Bank and Anderson Bank Company in 2005. Park National Bank Southwest Ohio & Northern Kentucky has eight branches; with Eastgate being classified as the main branch. They have locations in Milford, West Chester, Owensville, New Richmond, Eastgate, Ohio pike, Rookwood, and Anderson. The president of this division is Dave Gooch who started off with the company in Newark, Ohio (Park National Bank division). Park National Bank Southwest Ohio and Northern Kentucky is currently expanding with plans of adding a new branch in Louisville Kentucky.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cinci.parknationalbank.com/|title=Home - Park National Bank Southwest|website=Park National Bank Southwest|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref>\n\n=== United Bank ===\nThis affiliate started with the acquisition of United Bank, National Association in 2008. United Bank has six branches, the main branch is in Bucyrus. They have locations in Bucyrus, Galion, Caledonia, and Crestline. The president of this division is Donald Stone, who doubles as a commercial lender as well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unitedbankohio.com/|title=Home - United Bank of Ohio|website=United Bank of Ohio|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref>\n\n=== First-Knox National Bank ===\nThis affiliate started with the acquisition of First-Knox National Bank in 2008. First-Knox National has 13 branches, the main branch is in Mount Vernon. They have locations in Mount Vernon, Fredericktown, Utica, and Danville. The president of the First Knox division is Bob Boss. </ref>{{Cite web|url=https://firstknox.com/|title=Home - First Knox National Bank|website=First Knox National Bank|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Richland Bank ===\nThis affiliate started with the acquisition of The Richland Trust Company in 2008. Richland has ten branches, the main branch is in Mansfield. They have locations in Mansfield, Ontario, Lexington, and Shelby. The president of this division is Chris Hiner who is one half of their executive team. The other member of the executive team is Frank Wagner who is the executive vice president and a commercial lender.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://richlandbank.com/|title=Home - Richland Bank|website=Richland Bank|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Second National Bank ===\nThis affiliate started with the acquisition of Second National Bank in 2008. Second National has seven branches, the main branch is in Greenville. They have locations in Greenville, Arcanum, Versailles, and Ft. Recovery. The president of this division is John Swallow who started with the organization in Newark, Ohio.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://secondnational.com/|title=Home - Second National Bank|website=Second National Bank|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Security National Bank ===\nThis affiliate started with the acquisition of The Security National Bank and Trust Company in 2008. Security National has eighteen branches, the main branch is in Springfield. They have locations in Springfield, Enon, Medway, and New Carlisle. The president of this division is John Brown. This affiliate has the most branches out of every division that isn't including the main company Park National Bank.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://securitynationalbank.com/|title=Home - Security National Bank|website=Security National Bank|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Unity National Bank ===\nThis affiliate started off with the bank investing in Citizens National Bank of Urbana in 2008. Unity National has six branches, the main branch is in Piqua. They have locations in Piqua, Troy, and Tipp City. The president of this division of this division is Scott Rasor. Unity is the smallest affiliate that the Park National Family of Banks has.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unitynationalbk.com/|title=Home - Unity National Bank|website=Unity National Bank|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Century National Bank ===\nThis affiliate started off with the acquisition of Century National Bank in 2008. Century National has eighteen branches, the main branch is in Zanesville. They have locations in Zanesville, Dresden, New Concord, New Lexington, and Coshocton. The president of this division is Pat Nash. Century National also has eighteen branches, however the branches are closer to each other.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://centurynationalbank.com/|title=Home - Century National Bank|website=Century National Bank|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n[[Category:Companies listed on NYSE American]]\n[[Category:Banks based in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Companies based in the Columbus, Ohio metropolitan area]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{Refimprove|date=February 2013}}\n{{Notability|Companies|date=February 2013}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Park National Bank\n| logo             = [[File:Park National Bank logo 2013.png|250px|Park National Bank logo]]\n| former type      = \n| type             = [[Subsidiary]]\n| traded_as        = \n| industry         = Banking\n| fate             = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| foundation       = <!-- City, Country ({{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}}) -->\n| founder          = \n| defunct          = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| location_city    = \n| location_country = \n| locations        = <!-- Number of locations, stores, offices &c. -->\n| area_served      = {{ubl|[[Ohio]]|[[Kentucky]]|[[North Carolina]]}}\n| key_people       =  \n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = $84.2 million (2017)<ref name=\"ND Acq\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/columbus/news/2018/01/23/park-national-bank-to-buy-charlotte-based-bank-for.html |title=Park National Bank to buy Charlotte-based bank for $76M |last=Navera |first=Tristan |website=[[Columbus Business First]] |date=2018-01-23 |accessdate=2018-01-24}}</ref>\n| aum              = $7.5 billion (2017)<ref name=\"ND Acq\"/>\n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| owner            = \n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = Park National Corporation\n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = {{url|www.parknationalbank.com}}\n| footnotes        = \n}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Park National Corporation\n| traded_as = {{AMEX|PRK}}<br>[[Russell 2000 Index|Russell 2000 Component]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Park National Bank''' is the lead bank in the $7.5 billion Park National Corporation ({{AMEX|PRK}}) serving [[Ohio]] and Northern [[Kentucky]]. The bank has 10 affiliate banks, including: Fairfield National Bank; Park National Bank, Park National Bank: Southwest Ohio & Northern Kentucky; United Bank; First-Knox National Bank; Richland Bank; Second National Bank; Security National Bank; Unity National Bank; NewDominion Bank; Carolina Alliance Bank; Guardian Finance Company; Southeast Property Holdings; and Scope Leasing. Park National Bank is headquartered in [[Newark, Ohio]].\n\n== History ==\nPark National Bank was founded in July 1908 under the name The Park National Bank of Newark.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parknationalbank.com/|title=Home - Park National|website=Park National|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref> The organization changed its name to Park National Bank in 1971 shortly after acquiring The People's State Bank. The company then acquired The Utica Savings Bank Company in 1973, followed by The Fairfield National Bank of Lancaster.\n\nDuring the housing crisis of the early 2000's, Park National acquired nine other banks in a three year period.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bankbranchlocator.com/park-national-bank-history.html|title=Park National Bank History|website=www.bankbranchlocator.com|language=en|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref> Most of these acquisitions happened within the 2008 fiscal year, which was the peak of the crisis.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thebalance.com/mortgage-crisis-overview-315684|title=What (or Who) Caused the Mortgage Crisis?|work=The Balance|access-date=2018-11-02|language=en}}</ref> The company managed to acquire seven different banks in 2008. The next acquisition for the corporation was NewDominion Bank, which brought Park National into the North Carolina area. One of their affiliates has also recently announced plans to build a location in Kentucky.\n\nThe Carolina Alliance Bank is the latest bank to join the organization expanding the region into South Carolina.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newarkadvocate.com/story/news/2018/09/14/park-national-announces-plan-acquire-south-carolina-bank/1291606002/|title=Park National announces plan to acquire South Carolina bank|work=The Newark Advocate|access-date=2018-11-02|language=en}}</ref> The Park National Family of Banks is now operating in 28 counties in Ohio, one in Kentucky, one in North Carolina, and two in South Carolina. There are 110 branches located in Ohio.\n\n== Affiliates ==\n\n=== Fairfield National Bank ===\nThis affiliate started with the acquisition of The Fairfield National Bank of Lancaster in 1985. Fairfield National has nine branches, the main branch is in downtown Lancaster. They have locations in Lancaster, Baltimore, Pickerington, and Canal Winchester. The president of this division is Laura Tussing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fairfieldnationalbank.com/|title=Home - Fairfield National Bank|website=Fairfield National Bank|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Park National Bank: Southwest Ohio and Northern Kentucky ===\nThis affiliate started with the acquisition of First Clermont Bank and Anderson Bank Company in 2005. Park National Bank Southwest Ohio & Northern Kentucky has eight branches; with Eastgate being classified as the main branch. They have locations in Milford, West Chester, Owensville, New Richmond, Eastgate, Ohio pike, Rookwood, and Anderson. The president of this division is Dave Gooch who started off with the company in Newark, Ohio (Park National Bank division). Park National Bank Southwest Ohio and Northern Kentucky is currently expanding with plans of adding a new branch in Louisville Kentucky.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cinci.parknationalbank.com/|title=Home - Park National Bank Southwest|website=Park National Bank Southwest|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref>\n\n=== United Bank ===\nThis affiliate started with the acquisition of United Bank, National Association in 2008. United Bank has six branches, the main branch is in Bucyrus. They have locations in Bucyrus, Galion, Caledonia, and Crestline. The president of this division is Donald Stone, who doubles as a commercial lender as well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unitedbankohio.com/|title=Home - United Bank of Ohio|website=United Bank of Ohio|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref>\n\n=== First-Knox National Bank ===\nThis affiliate started with the acquisition of First-Knox National Bank in 2008. First-Knox National has 13 branches, the main branch is in Mount Vernon. They have locations in Mount Vernon, Fredericktown, Utica, and Danville. The president of the First Knox division is Bob Boss. </ref>{{Cite web|url=https://firstknox.com/|title=Home - First Knox National Bank|website=First Knox National Bank|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Richland Bank ===\nThis affiliate started with the acquisition of The Richland Trust Company in 2008. Richland has ten branches, the main branch is in Mansfield. They have locations in Mansfield, Ontario, Lexington, and Shelby. The president of this division is Chris Hiner who is one half of their executive team. The other member of the executive team is Frank Wagner who is the executive vice president and a commercial lender.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://richlandbank.com/|title=Home - Richland Bank|website=Richland Bank|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Second National Bank ===\nThis affiliate started with the acquisition of Second National Bank in 2008. Second National has seven branches, the main branch is in Greenville. They have locations in Greenville, Arcanum, Versailles, and Ft. Recovery. The president of this division is John Swallow who started with the organization in Newark, Ohio.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://secondnational.com/|title=Home - Second National Bank|website=Second National Bank|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Security National Bank ===\nThis affiliate started with the acquisition of The Security National Bank and Trust Company in 2008. Security National has eighteen branches, the main branch is in Springfield. They have locations in Springfield, Enon, Medway, and New Carlisle. The president of this division is John Brown. This affiliate has the most branches out of every division that isn't including the main company Park National Bank.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://securitynationalbank.com/|title=Home - Security National Bank|website=Security National Bank|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Unity National Bank ===\nThis affiliate started off with the bank investing in Citizens National Bank of Urbana in 2008. Unity National has six branches, the main branch is in Piqua. They have locations in Piqua, Troy, and Tipp City. The president of this division of this division is Scott Rasor. Unity is the smallest affiliate that the Park National Family of Banks has.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unitynationalbk.com/|title=Home - Unity National Bank|website=Unity National Bank|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref>\n\n=== Century National Bank ===\nThis affiliate started off with the acquisition of Century National Bank in 2008. Century National has eighteen branches, the main branch is in Zanesville. They have locations in Zanesville, Dresden, New Concord, New Lexington, and Coshocton. The president of this division is Pat Nash. Century National also has eighteen branches, however the branches are closer to each other.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://centurynationalbank.com/|title=Home - Century National Bank|website=Century National Bank|language=en-US|access-date=2018-11-02}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n[[Category:Companies listed on NYSE American]]\n[[Category:Banks based in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Companies based in the Columbus, Ohio metropolitan area]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Park_National_Bank_(Ohio)"}
{"title_page": "1998\u201399 Cypriot Fourth Division", "text_new": "{{Infobox football league season\n| competition = [[Cypriot Fourth Division]]\n| season      = 1998\u201399\n| winners     = [[ENTHOI Lakatamia FC|THOI Lak.]]<br/>(1st title)\n| promoted    = [[ENTHOI Lakatamia FC|THOI Lak.]]<br>[[Kinyras Empas|Kinyras]]<br>[[Ellinismos Akakiou|Ellinismos]]\n| relegated   = [[Anagennisi Prosfigon Ayiou Antoniou Lemesou|Anagennisi Pr.]]<br>[[AOL Omonia Lakatamias|AOL Omonia]]<br>[[Poseidonas Giolou|Poseidonas]]<br>[[Evagoras Kato Amiandos|Evagoras]]\n| matches     = 210\n| total goals = 613\n| prevseason  = [[1997\u201398 Cypriot Fourth Division|1997\u201398]]\n| nextseason  = [[1999\u20132000 Cypriot Fourth Division|1999\u201300]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1998\u201399 Cypriot Fourth Division''' was the 14th season of the Cypriot fourth-level [[Association football|football]] league. [[ENTHOI Lakatamia FC|THOI Lakatamia]] won their 1st title.\n\n==Format==\nFourteen teams participated in the 1998\u201399 Cypriot Fourth Division. All teams played against each other twice, once at their home and once away. The team with the most points at the end of the season crowned champions. The first three teams were promoted to the [[1999\u20132000 Cypriot Third Division]] and the last four teams were relegated to regional leagues.\n\n===Point system===\nTeams received three points for a win, one point for a draw and zero points for a loss.\n\n==Changes from previous season==\n'''Teams promoted to [[1998\u201399 Cypriot Third Division]]'''\n* [[SEK Agiou Athanasiou]]\n* [[ATE PEK Ergaton]]\n* [[Doxa Paliometochou]]\n\n'''Teams relegated from [[1997\u201398 Cypriot Third Division]]'''\n* [[AEK Kakopetrias]]\n* [[Kinyras Empas]]\n* [[ENTHOI Lakatamia FC|THOI Lakatamia]]\n\n'''Teams promoted from regional leagues'''\n* [[AOL Omonia Lakatamias]]\n* [[AEK Kythreas]]\n* [[AMEP Parekklisia]]\n* [[MEAP Nisou]]\n\n'''Teams relegated to regional leagues'''\n* [[Anorthosis Kato Polemidia|Anorthosi{{typo help inline|reason=similar to Anorthose|date=March 2020}} Polemidion]]\n* Salamina Dromolaxias\n* [[Fotiakos Frenarou]]\n\n==League standings==\n{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|res_col_header=PR\n\n|team1=THL|name_THL=[[ENTHOI Lakatamia FC|THOI Lakatamia]]\n|team2=KNR|name_KNR=[[Kinyras Empas]]\n|team3=ELN|name_ELN=[[Ellinismos Akakiou]]\n|team4=MPN|name_MPN=[[MEAP Nisou]]\n|team5=THA|name_THA=[[Th.O.I. Avgorou FC]]\n|team6=AKT|name_AKT=[[AEK Kythreas]]\n|team7=AMP|name_AMP=[[AMEP Parekklisia]]\n|team8=AKK|name_AKK=[[AEK Kakopetrias]]\n|team9=AMK|name_AMK=[[AMEK Kapsalou]]\n|team10=APL|name_APL=[[Apollon Lympion]]\n|team11=ORF|name_ORF=[[Orfeas Nicosia]]\n|team12=ANG|name_ANG=[[Anagennisi Prosfigon Ayiou Antoniou Lemesou|Anagennisi Prosfigon]]\n|team13=AOL|name_AOL=[[AOL Omonia Lakatamias|AOL Omonia]]\n|team14=PSD|name_PSD=[[Poseidonas Giolou]]\n|team15=EGR|name_EGR=[[Evagoras Kato Amiandos|Evagoras Kato Amiantos]]\n|win_THL=17|draw_THL=5|loss_THL=6|gf_THL=54|ga_THL=24|status_THL=C,P\n|win_KNR=16|draw_KNR=7|loss_KNR=5|gf_KNR=40|ga_KNR=22|status_KNR=P\n|win_ELN=14|draw_ELN=7|loss_ELN=7|gf_ELN=48|ga_ELN=21|status_ELN=P\n|win_MPN=13|draw_MPN=6|loss_MPN=9|gf_MPN=44|ga_MPN=35\n|win_THA=13|draw_THA=6|loss_THA=9|gf_THA=44|ga_THA=37\n|win_AKT=13|draw_AKT=6|loss_AKT=9|gf_AKT=37|ga_AKT=38\n|win_AMP=13|draw_AMP=3|loss_AMP=12|gf_AMP=44|ga_AMP=36\n|win_AKK=12|draw_AKK=5|loss_AKK=11|gf_AKK=40|ga_AKK=41\n|win_AMK=11|draw_AMK=7|loss_AMK=10|gf_AMK=44|ga_AMK=34\n|win_APL=10|draw_APL=7|loss_APL=11|gf_APL=47|ga_APL=41\n|win_ORF=9|draw_ORF=6|loss_ORF=13|gf_ORF=44|ga_ORF=47\n|win_ANG=8|draw_ANG=7|loss_ANG=13|gf_ANG=30|ga_ANG=43|status_ANG=R\n|win_AOL=8|draw_AOL=6|loss_AOL=14|gf_AOL=36|ga_AOL=43|status_AOL=R\n|win_PSD=5|draw_PSD=4|loss_PSD=19|gf_PSD=31|ga_PSD=60|status_PSD=R\n|win_EGR=4|draw_EGR=6|loss_EGR=18|gf_EGR=30|ga_EGR=91|status_EGR=R\n\n|col_P=green1|text_P=Promoted to [[1999\u20132000 Cypriot Third Division|Cypriot Third Division]]\n|result1=P|result2=P|result3=P\n|col